stack@... wrote:

&gt;Sharad Agarwal wrote:
&gt;  
&gt;
&gt;&gt;We had the requirement of scaling heritrix. We have done it by employing
&gt;&gt;Consistent hashing scheme. The hashing scheme splits the url space based
&gt;&gt;on domain (so that politness is ensured) on which each heritrix instance
&gt;&gt;work on. The whole set up is controller less; each node has the hashing
&gt;&gt;function. Whenever a out of node&#39;s scope url is found, it is sent to the
&gt;&gt;node owning it. These urls are collected and sent in batches to the
&gt;&gt;owning nodes via JMX by a separate thread.
&gt;&gt;The architecture looks to be scalable in the sense that there is no
&gt;&gt;controller bottleneck. All heritrix node are identical. The whole scheme
&gt;&gt;is working pretty fine for us. We have gone quite a few millions with
&gt;&gt;3-4 heritrix instance nodes.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;Sounds sweet.
&gt;
&gt;+ Did you use the ubicrawler ConsistentHashFunction implementation that 
&gt;is in Heritrix in the dsi.unimi.it jar or did you use something else?
&gt;  
&gt;
yes. the same one.

&gt;+ If, lets say, a hostmaster complained you were hitting her servers too 
&gt;hard, how did you figure which of the crawlers the domain had landed 
&gt;on?  (Was it a problem for you that its effectively opaque which domain 
&gt;landed on which server?)
&gt;  
&gt;

this can be done via a simple utility. just call the same hashing fn instance passing the uri, it will tell the node owning it.
we didn&#39;t face any problem due to this opaqueness. 
also same domain lands on the same server across server restarts (courtesy consistent hashing); making it easy for maintenance.

&gt;+ Do you have anything to say about how well the load was balanced 
&gt;across the crawlers in practise.  I understand that in theory the load 
&gt;should be evenly distributed but I wonder how the practise was.  Could 
&gt;you adjust how much load a machine was carrying post startup?
&gt;  
&gt;

The load is fairly balanced with even 2-3 nodes. As the number of nodes increase, my assumption is it will even balance more.
We do have the mechanism of adding nodes at the runtime which inturn updates the hashing fn of all running nodes; and load is balanced.
Fine tuning the load with same number of nodes is not done yet. This can be done by introduction of mapping of multiple buckets to a single node. 
Currently one node has just 1 bucket. For tuning, one might shift buckets from heavily loaded node to another node. 

&gt;+ Is the code proprietary and if not, would you mind sharing it?
&gt;  
&gt;

We do have plans for making the code public. Some work has to be done to integrate it with the latest heritrix release. Ours uses 1.6. Also it has to branch off from our current project code base. We have done many enhancements like focus crawling, host priortization etc. So I beleive it has to be a phased thing to get into the current branch.

Sharad

&gt;Good stuff,
&gt;St.Ack
