&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;Cool. Anyways my thoughts on splitting the architecture were to split
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;the Processors across various machines. Have a Statistics server
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;maintain statistics, and a single frontier.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;        
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;Here&#39;s a few items you&#39;d have to contend with if you split Heritrix:
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;+ You&#39;ll have to spend alot of resources serializing and deserializing
&gt;&gt;&gt;passing rich URLs and configurations.
&gt;&gt;&gt;+ Certain processors, as written, expect to find on local disk the
&gt;&gt;&gt;downloaded resources (You could share them using NFS. NFS won&#39;t take
&gt;&gt;&gt;too kindly to the crawler&#39;s heavy I/O).
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;      
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;My idea was to have
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;frontier emit a batch of URLS to the processore boxes, hence instead
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;of next() you have nextBatch(). Anyways, I guess this involves a lot
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;of work, hence I am going in for a Peer2Peer setup, with fully loaded
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;agents doing the URL splits and emmitting batches to the others. I am
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;wondering however on the efficiency of JMX with RMI connectors to do
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;this Job. Do you think going the plain RMI way would be faster?
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;        
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;We haven&#39;t measured. JMX is heavyweight but works.
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;One suggestion has been to use JGroups. Friends of Heritrix were
&gt;&gt;&gt;experimenting making a &#39;cluster&#39; subclass of Frontier. On
&gt;&gt;&gt;initialization, it joined a JGroups group and listened in for URL
&gt;&gt;&gt;broadcasts. Those that fit its portion of the URL space, it picked off
&gt;&gt;&gt;the bus and added to the local Frontier. Those URLs meant for another
&gt;&gt;&gt;crawler, were broadcast (They&#39;ve said they&#39;ll write the list if findings
&gt;&gt;&gt;prove promising).
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;But depends on your requirements. Joe Hungs&#39; group didn&#39;t bother
&gt;&gt;&gt;swapping URLs across the cluster. Their experience was that the
&gt;&gt;&gt;crawlers had sufficient work without exchanging URLs and figured that
&gt;&gt;&gt;each crawler would discover its URL-segment important pages anyways
&gt;&gt;&gt;without having to have injection from peers (I don&#39;t know if they
&gt;&gt;&gt;&#39;proved&#39; this assertion).
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
